        <div xml:id="AN7-kilavi"></div>
        <div xml:id="AN7">
            <lg type="edition"><l>mulaimukañ ceytaṉa muḷḷeyi ṟilaṅkiṉa</l>
<l>talaimuṭi cāṉṟa taṇṭaḻai yuṭaiyai</l>
<l>yalamara lāyamō <choice><seg>ṭāṅkaṇum</seg><seg>ṭaṅkaṇum</seg></choice> paṭāaṉ</l>
<l>mūppuṭai <choice><seg>mutupati</seg><seg>mutupatit</seg></choice> tākkaṇaṅ kuṭaiya</l>
<l>kāppum pūṇṭiciṟ kaṭaiyum <choice><seg>pōkal</seg><seg>pōkalai</seg></choice></l>
<l>pētai yallai <choice><seg>pētaiyaṅ</seg><seg>mētaiyaṅ</seg></choice> kuṟumakaḷ</l>
<l>petumpaip paruvat totuṅkiṉai puṟatteṉa</l>
<l>voṇcuṭar nalli laruṅkaṭi nīvit</l>
<l>taṉcitai vaṟita lañci yiṉcilai</l>
<l>yēṟuṭai yiṉatta nāṟuyir navvi</l>
<l>valaikāṇ <choice><seg>piṇaiyiṟ</seg><seg>piṇaiyi</seg></choice> <choice><seg>pōki</seg><seg>ṉotuṅki</seg></choice> yīṅkōr</l>
<l>tolaivil veḷvēl viṭalaiyō ṭeṉmaka</l>
<l>ḷiccuram paṭartan tōḷē yāyiṭai</l>
<l>yattak kaḷva rātoḻu vaṟutteṉap</l>
<l><choice><seg>piṟpaṭu</seg><seg>piṟappaṭu</seg></choice> pūcaliṉ vaḻivaḻi yōṭi</l>
<l>meyttalaip paṭutal cellē ṉittalai</l>
<l>niṉṉoṭu viṉavuval kēḷāy poṉṉoṭu</l>
<l>pulippaṟ kōtta pulampumaṇit tāli</l>
<l>yolikkuḻaic ceyalai yuṭaimā ṇalku</l>
<l>lāycuḷaip palaviṉ mēykalai yutirtta</l>
<l>tuyttalai veṇkāḻ peṟūuṅ</l>
<l>kaṟkeḻu ciṟukuṭik <choice><seg>kāṉavaṉ</seg><seg>kāṉavar</seg></choice> makaḷē.</l></lg>
            <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>“[Your] breasts have taken form. [Your] thorn teeth shine.</l>
<l>You possess cool foliage that is worthy of a head knot.<note place="foot">The line is problematic.  One way is to read it as an eliptical allusion to her growing up: we know that taḻai is not worn on the head but tied into a leaf skirt.  The whole phrase then might mean that if she is grown-up enough to wear a leaf skirt she should also wear her hair in a knot.  Another interpretation is given by the old commentary: if we read cāṉṟa not as a peyareccam but as a short form of the n.pl., the line splits into two separate sentences (“Your head knot is full. You possess cool foliage.”), and the commentator explains the plural, awkward for one knot, as referring to the fact that she has a lot of hair.</note></l>
<l>Don’t be there too with [your] companions who mill about.</l>
<l>Possessing ripe age, the old abodes are full of evil spirits that attack.</l>
<l>Be on [your] <choice><seg>guard </seg><seg>guard, </seg></choice> <choice><seg>and </seg><seg>and you </seg></choice> don’t go [beyond] the limits [of our compound]!</l>
<l>You are no little girl, [my] <choice><seg>silly </seg><seg>clever </seg></choice> little daughter.</l>
<l>You have stepped outside the age of a girl,”</l>
<l>brushing [past] the heavy protection of the brightly glowing good house,</l>
<l>afraid of [my] knowing of her being spoilt, [my] doe</l>
<l>with fragrant breath from a herd with a sweetly resounding bull</l>
<l><choice><seg>going </seg><seg>retreating </seg></choice> like a doe seeing a net, my daughter</l>
<l>together with a warrior of undefeated white spear here</l>
<l>set out <choice><seg>into </seg><seg>in to </seg></choice> this desert.</l>
<l rend="indent">	In between,</l>
<l rend="indent">	because the robbers on the road had cut open the cow manger,</l>
<l rend="indent">	in the clamour happening <choice><seg>afterwards, </seg><seg>otherwise, </seg></choice> running every way</l>
<l>I did not manage<note place="foot">This is the first of a number of passages where cel is used as an auxiliary, conveying the sense of capacity: “I could not find [them]”.  There are a few possible parallels to such a usage, none of them, however, unequivocal; cf. KT 159.1, 265.1, 287.4, 340.3.  Clearer are the parallels in the AN itself, namely AN 14.14 and 19.6.</note> to find [them] in the body.</l>
<l rend="indent">	On this account</l>
<l>I inquire with you, listen,</l>
<l>daughter of the forest <choice><seg>man </seg><seg>people </seg></choice> from a stony little hamlet,</l>
<l rend="indent">	where the monkey feeding on jackfruit with choice pulp</l>
<l rend="indent">	obtains the soft-headed white seeds that had dropped,</l>
<l>[your] Tāli of a solitary gem tied with tiger teeth and gold,</l>
<l>your hips glorious dressed with Aśoka in fresh sprouts.</l></lg>
        </div>
    </body>
